@starimpact I'm still trying to track the root cause. A straightforward way would be printing out the gradients of all operators. We can add print statements in this function: https://github.com/dmlc/mxnet/blob/master/src/executor/attach_op_execs_pass.cc#L138

Another method is to make a much simpler example with fewer operators, but this may actually require more work.

I'll try these the first method tomorrow.

Does the slow down happen if you feed dummy data with iterator like this:
```

class DummyIter(mx.io.DataIter):
    def __init__(self, batch_size, data_shape):
        self.data_shape = (batch_size,) + data_shape
        self.label_shape = (batch_size,)
        self.provide_data = [('data', self.data_shape)]
        self.provide_label = [('softmax_label', self.label_shape)]

    def next(self):
        return mx.io.DataBatch(data=[mx.nd.zeros(self.data_shape)],
                               label=[mx.nd.zeros(self.label_shape)])
```
